ologists and neurosurgeons, meanwhile, have used material apparatus—the scalpel, the electrode—to probe the workings of the nervous system, and in so doing have radically reshaped our understanding of the brain. Both operate in vastly different institutional and cultural contexts. Given these differences, it is remarkable that both fields found resources for their development in the same tradition of late nineteenth-century German medicine: neuropsychiatry. In Localization and Its Discontents, Katja Guenther investigates the significance of this common history, drawing on extensive archival research in seven countries, institutional analysis, and close examination of the practical conditions of scientific and clinical work. Her remarkable accomplishment not only reframes the history of psychoanalysis and the neuro disciplines, but also offers us new ways of thinking about their future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNeurologyxHistory 0aNeurologyxHistory. 0aNeurosciencesxHistory. 0aPsychiatryxHistory. 0aPsychoanalysisxHistory. 0aPsychophysiology - History. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apsychoanalysis, medical history, neurology, neurological medicine, psychoanalysts, spoken word, therapeutic practice, neurosurgeons, nervous system, neuropsychiatry, neuro disciplines, institutional analysis, clinical work, neurosciences, biology, psychology, pathological anatomy, sigmund freud, reflex therapy, motor functions, psychiatry, theodor meynert, otfrid foerster, wilder penfield, carl wernicke, paul schilder.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022628820840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226288345423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226288345/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  Un